<subSubSection lastPageId="214" lastPageNumber="215" pageId="213" pageNumber="214" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="213" pageNumber="214">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="214" lastPageNumber="215" pageId="213" pageNumber="214">
This species, also known as the &quot;Margined Tiger Beetle&quot;, is found along the Atlantic Coast from Kings County in Nova Scotia (Neil and Majka 2008: 
<pageBreakToken pageId="214" pageNumber="215" start="start">4</pageBreakToken>
) to the Florida Keys and along the Gulf Coast in Florida [see Pearson et al. 2006: Map 96]; it is also recorded from the Bahamas and Cuba (Peck 2005: 27). According to Dunn (1983: 4), the species has declined significantly along the New Hampshire coast.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
